# Simulate the sequential transformations.
# Note: In Gulf, the element is accessed as m[a-1] where a = counter % 39.
# Since Gulf arrays are 1-offset (m[-1] is the first element, m[0] the second, etc.)
# we simulate this by mapping m[a-1] to m[a] in our Python list.
for key in keys:
    a = counter % 39   # a is set to (counter mod 39)
    i = a              # because m[a-1] in Gulf maps to m[a] in Python
    v = m[i]
    w = ((counter ^ v) % 256) ^ key
    m[i] = w
    counter += 1

print("Final m =", m)
